'''Roy Anthony Cutaran Bennett''' (born 1913 April 6, [[Bayombong]], [[Cagayan Valley]], [[Philippines]]''';''' died 1990 November 11, [[Rosemead, California]], USA) was the outspoken editor of the ''[[Manila Bulletin]]'' before and during the [[Japanese invasion of the Philippines]].<ref>{{cite news
|url = http://www.geni.com/people/Roy-Anthony-Bennett/6000000011626535516 
|title = Roy Anthony Cutaran Bennett (1913-1990) 
|magazine = Geni 
|first = Mona 
|last = Magno-Veluz 
|date = 2011-03-02
|accessdate = 2012-10-29
}}</ref>

For 13 months prior to liberation of the Philippines by American forces in 1944, Bennett was imprisoned and tortured in [[Santo Tomas]] by the Japanese for his writings opposing the military expansion of the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese Empire]].<ref>{{cite news
|magazine = History Channel
|date = 2012-10-29
|title = Modern marvels
|issue = Torture devices
|accessdate = 2012-10-29
}}</ref>

Bennett was the four children of Roy DeWitt Bennett (1884-1968)<ref>{{cite news
|url = http://angkangpilipino.com/2011/06/21/bios-of-notable-thomasites/#bennett 
|title = Bios of notable Thomasites
|magazine = Angkan Pilipino
|accessdate = 2012-10-29
|date = 2011-06-21
}}</ref> and Josefa Camaguian Cutaran Bennett (1884-1949).<ref>{{cite news
|url = http://www.geni.com/people/Josefa-Cutaran/6000000011626672403 
|title = Josefa Camaguian Cutaran Bennett (1884-1949) 
|first = Mona 
|last = Magno-Veluz
|date = 2011-03-02 
|magazine = Geni
|accessdate = 2012-10-29
}}</ref> Roy Anthony Cutaran Bennett's daughter Helen Cutaran Bennett became [[Foreign Secretary]] for [[Republic of the Philippines#Government|Philippine President]] [[Elpidio Quirino]]. 

